  "prompt": "In Tagalog, what are the rules for using Nang and Ng?",
  "response": "In Tagalog, \"nang\" and \"ng\" have distinct uses and are not interchangeable. Here are some guidelines for using each:\n\n### Nang\n1. **Adverbial Use**: \"Nang\" is used to form adverbs. It is often used to answer questions like \"paano\" (how). For example, \"Tumakbo siya nang mabilis\" (He ran quickly).\n\n2. **Conjunction**: It is used as a conjunction equivalent to \"when\" or \"so that\". For example, \"Umalis siya nang dumating ako\" (He left when I arrived).\n\n3. **To Show Manner**: It indicates the manner of an action, similar to \"in order to\" or \"so that\". For example, \"Nag-aral siya nang mabuti\" (He studied well).\n\n4. **Repetition**: Used to indicate repeated actions, similar to \"every time\" or \"each time\". For example, \"Nang nangyari iyon\" (When that happened).\n\n5. **Before a Verb**: It is used before a verb to indicate the reason or purpose, similar to \"to\" or \"in order to\". For example, \"Pumunta siya nang makita ka\" (He went to see you).\n\n### Ng\n1. **Possession**: \"Ng\" indicates possession, similar to the English word \"of\". For example, \"Aklat ng bata\" (The child's book).\n\n2. **Object of the Verb**: It is used to mark the direct object of a verb. For example, \"Kumain ng mansanas\" (Ate an apple).\n\n3. **Part of a Whole**: Used to indicate a part of a whole. For example, \"Kalahati ng tinapay\" (Half of the bread).\n\n4. **Subject of an Adjective**: When used with an adjective, \"ng\" indicates the subject of the adjective. For example, \"Maganda ng bulaklak\" (The flower is beautiful).\n\nUnderstanding these distinctions is important for proper grammar and meaning in Tagalog.",
